<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-834-614  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 834 614.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  July 1990 v112 n1 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Focus on software. (needed: an unobstructed view of Windows 3)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whitmyer, Claude F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Windows 3.0 graphical user interface comes very close tolooking and acting like the GUI of the Apple Macintosh.andP;  However,users are finding it difficult to install and use the product.andO;Despite these initial problems, Microsoft is expected to succeedin selling Windows 3.0 because it is a definite improvement overthe older versions and the company is offering a $50 upgrade.andO;There are also about 30 million IBM-type machines installed thatare capable of running the GUI.andP;  Many observers foresee that theMacintosh market will diminish with Windows 3.0 providing stiffcompetition.andP;  The issue could boil down to price vs functionality:the Macintosh generally is easier to install and use but IBMmachines are cheaper.andP;  While Windows 3.0 will sell, it still has along way to go to equal the Macintosh GUI.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (design andconstruction)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceComparison.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>